NAME
       simple_shell - a simple UNIX command interpreter

SYNOPSIS
       simple_shell

DESCRIPTION
       The simple_shell is a command interpreter that reads commands from standard
       input and executes them. It is intended to work similar to the standard UNIX
       shell /bin/sh.

INVOCATION
       simple_shell is started from the command line.

       simple_shell
              Starts the shell in interactive mode.

       echo "command" | simple_shell
              Starts the shell in non-interactive mode.

BUILTINS
       The simple_shell supports the following built-in commands:

       exit [status]
              Causes the shell to exit with the given status. If no status is given,
              the shell exits with the status of the last command executed.

       env
              Prints the current environment.

       cd [directory]
              Changes the current working directory to directory. If no directory is
              given, the shell changes to the home directory.

COMMAND EXECUTION
       The simple_shell searches for commands in the directories specified by the
       PATH environment variable. If a command is found, it is executed with the
       given arguments.

SIGNALS
       The simple_shell handles the SIGINT signal (Ctrl+C) by ignoring it and
       continuing to read input.

EXIT STATUS
       The exit status of a command is the exit status of the process in which it
       was executed.

       If a command is not found, the exit status is 127.

       If a command is found but cannot be executed, the exit status is 126.

EXAMPLES
       Interactive mode:
              $ ./simple_shell
              ($) /bin/ls
              hsh main.c shell.c
              ($) exit
              $

       Non-interactive mode:
              $ echo "/bin/ls" | ./simple_shell
              hsh main.c shell.c
              $

